<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAMESE AND THE WALL</font><br>
<tt>Mon Apr 28 22:07:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc, your inablilty to express why you could not/chose not to communicate with others at the Wall, could it have been just because of the general mood of reverence and contemplation and nothing more? Or do you take this as a racial divide at that time and place?<br><br>
One other thing that occured to me.  For many of us vets, the war ended and we have our scars. For many American who did not go over, they have their scars. The war cost us a lot, not just in lives, but on the effects that the war had on us as individuals and as a nation. Depending how you look at it, some have said that we lost the war. Others(Tanker, where are you?)say we were winning the war when we left. In either case, the North rolled into Saigon.<br><br>
With that said, we did not lose our country. We did not have to give up our land that we were born on. The South Vietnamese did lose a country and everything that goes with it. These refugees lost their home, they did not forfeit their country to come over here just to have a better life. In most cases, it was leave or suffer the consequences. As everbody that has a family knows, I'm positive that the choices that they made were based on what was best for their love ones. <br><br>
Some can argue with me one this point, but we hold some responsibility for these people and for those who did not get out. The US made some pretty firm commitments to South Vietnam that were not lived up to as pointed out by Betty on another thread.<br><br>
The issue with the flags is stupid. If god damn McDonalds can fly their flag along side the American Flag, why can not these folks fly theirs in accordance with the laws in regards to position to the US flag.  We fly flags that have no bearing to any nation along side our US flag. I fly an American flag, a South Vietnamese Flag and a POW/MIA flag. I'll be damned if anyone tells me it would be inappropriate. The city council screwed up on this one.<br><br>
An yet, it was very magnanimous of the Vietnamese to have hosted the Wall. It was something they did not have to do. It was a mighty damn fine gesture, to say the least. I wish I was there to have seen it.
